Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Hichem Dridi¶

I. Introduction¶

Data analysis has used many tools to find answers to business problems and questions, one of these most widely used tools is data visualization, it is very effective for data exploration and for analysis. explanation of the results. With the right graphic and an appropriate story, you can get your point across to anyone.

In this notebook, we'll explore data from a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay Area. The data is known as Ford GoBike System Data and can be downloaded from Kaggle. Each line contains various information about an individual trip such as duration, departure and arrival station, bike, etc. Brief Description of Data Each ride is anonymized and includes:

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
  • Start Time and Date
  • End Time and Date
  • Start Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude
  • End Station ID
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Bike ID
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer — “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual)
  • Member Year of Birth
  • Member Gender

183412 rows × 16 columns

The dataset contains information on 183,412 trips divided into 16 different columns. Most of the features describe the ride on itself while only three of them present information about the user (user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender).

At first glance, we may be dealing with missing values (this mostly shows up for the birth year and gender columns) and the wrong data type for station IDs. Otherwise, the data looks good to work with.

Let's take a deep look into the dataset:

A quick look at the data structure reveals:

  • The columns that indicate the start and end times of trips are of the object type.
  • Missing information on departure and/or arrival stations for some recordings.

2. Data Cleaning¶

The dataset for bike rides requires cleaning for the following quality issues:

  • Object data type values of datetime columns (start_time and end_time).
  • Missing data of station identifiers and names (cannot be cleaned).
  • Inaccurate values of latitudes and longitudes.
  • The columns of the identifiers and the geographic coordinates are of numeric type.
  • The user_type, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip columns have object type data.
  • No data on member's gender and/or year of birth (cannot be cleaned).
  • Users over the age of 100 (just noted).

Fortunately, there are no tidiness errors.

In [15]:

# a function that extract the hour and day name from a given column
def hour_day_extract(dataframe, column):
    col_loc = dataframe.columns.get_loc(column) # get column location
    prefix = column.split("_")[0] # start or end
    # insert hour column
    dataframe.insert(col_loc + 1, prefix + "_hour", dataframe[column].dt.hour)
    # insert day name column
    dataframe.insert(col_loc + 2, prefix + "_day", dataframe[column].dt.day_name())
    # convert day name column to ordinal
    days_list = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday',
                'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
    orderd_days = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = days_list)
    dataframe[prefix + "_day"] = dataframe[prefix + "_day"].astype(orderd_days)
    # insert an indication for the weekend 
    dataframe.insert(col_loc + 3, prefix + "_IsWeekend", dataframe[column].dt.day_name().isin(['Saturday', 'Sunday']))

4. Summary¶

The original dataset we started with contains information on 183,412 bike trips divided into 16 different columns that describe trip time, stations, date, user, and more. With some cleanup and feature engineering, that number of columns grew to 22, I've only kept 14 for the analysis part.

My interest in this notebook is to find out which factors influence the duration of the bike ride and where and when there is a greater bike usage.

I mainly think the day and time of the journey affect the duration, for example I expect to have shorter journeys on weekdays but higher use of the bikes on weekends. I also want to know the effect of departure and arrival points (station and/or city) and available user data on the feature I'm interested in.

# create a new column called journey
bikes_df['journey'] = bikes_df['start_station_name'] + " - " + bikes_df['end_station_name']

Multivariate Exploration Summary¶

The time-day combination not only has an influence on the use of bicycles, but also on the duration of journeys. While users take shorter trips on weekdays, they prefer to take longer bike rides on weekends in the early morning and mid-day.

Another interesting finding is how the interaction between the three user-related variables influences trip duration. Regardless of the age category, the men's bike rides are very short, where the female clientele tends to be longer.

V. Conclusions¶

In this notebook, I analyzed the bike trip data provided by Ford GoBike System, mainly we had 183,412 trips divided into 16 different columns. The data required cleaning and transformation, after which I proceeded to the exploration phase.

Bike trip data was primarily collected from stations in San Francisco, with other trips taken in nearby cities like Berkeley, Oakland, Emeryville, etc. This bike sharing system is mainly used by subscribers, men and young users.

The main variable of interest is Duration, I discovered, with logarithmic transformation, that most recorded bike rides lasted less than half an hour, with a peak around ten minutes.

I was also interested in the evolution of hourly and daily bicycle use, weekdays and times when people tend to commute from home to work and vice versa had the highest use of bicycles. On the other side, weekeends have the greatest average bike rides duration, especially in the middle of the day.

Some routes were used by users more than others, where most riders depart from Berry St at 4th St to arrive at San Francisco Ferry Building and take the route from Grand Ave to 19th Street BART Station during the weekdays by For example, on Sundays, locals take other routes like taking a ride around Golden Park using the bikes from Fell St Station to Stanyan St.

Finally, I found that the longest bike trips are associated with customers, especially female customers and old customers, men on the other hand make very short trips on average for different age categories.
